The fluorescence quenching efficiency ((F0–F)/F0) and UV absorbance rate ((A0−A)/A0) of the purified RbB-CDs decreased when As3+ concentrations increased (0–50 μg/L) (Fig. 5
                        a and c). It was linear with As3+ concentrations (0–5 μg/L, R2 = 0.99312; 10–50 μg/L, R2 = 0.99046) with the low detection limits (LOD) of 0.75 μg/L and 5.00 μg/L, respectively (Fig. 5b) (Table 1
                        ) [27–37]. Based on the relative atomic mass of As is 74.9216, so 0.75 μg/L equals 10.01 nM and 5 μg/L equals 66.74 nM. The UV absorbance rate of the purified RbB-CDs was linear with As3+ concentrations (0–50 μg/L, R2 = 0.99209) with a LOD of 3.03 μg/L (40.44 nM) (Fig. 5d). It is important and interesting to compare the method with other relevant methods for arsenic and metal ions detection based on fluorescent carbon dots. Bu et al. reported the green-emitting carbon quantum dots as a dual-mode fluorescent and colorimetric sensor for hypochlorite detection, with LODs of 781 nM and 1820 nM, respectively [38]. Wang et al. reported a novel colorimetric and fluorometric probe based on amorphous carbon nanodots as the dual-mode and reversible detection of Hg2+ and glutathione (GSH), and the LODs with fluorometric and colorimetric for Hg2+ were 6.8 nM and 380 nM, and for GSH were 10.9 nM and 560 nM, respectively [39]. Ge et al. developed the on-site detection of As3+ based on silver nanoparticles HH@Ag NPs aggregation mediated by phosphates using surface-enhanced Raman scattering, with a LOD of 1.8 nM [40].
